"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540955","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-05","<p>An updated Ministerial Code will be published in due course.</p><p>The business appointment rules already apply to former Ministers taking up any new or unpaid appointment within two years of leaving Ministerial office. The guidance can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/new-business-appointments-for-senior-public-servants" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/new-business-appointments-for-senior-public-servants</a></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-09-05T08:29:44.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540955/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540955/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-20","Ministers: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether he plans to amend the Ministerial Code to include the full text of the rules on business appointments.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","43484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540956","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-05","<p>As part of my introduction to the Cabinet Office, I plan to meet the Chairmen of the Cabinet Office sponsored NDPBs to discuss the workings of their respective Bodies and this will include the Chairman of the Advisory Committee on Business Appointments following which I will reply to the Chairman's letter.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-09-05T08:29:56.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540956/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540956/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-20","Business Appointments Advisory Committee: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when his Department plans to respond to the letter sent to it by the Chair of the Advisory Committee on Business Appointments in November 2015.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","43485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540957","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-05","<p>We have made huge progress in building a Northern Powerhouse, from investment in transport, enterprise and culture to agreeing five landmark devolution deals across the North. We remain fully committed to doing everything we can to strengthen the Northern Powerhouse, including investing £13bn in transport over the course of this parliament, further improving skills through the Northern Powerhouse Schools Strategy and encouraging even more foreign investment into the towns and cities of the North. Next year, 55% of the North’s population will vote for a mayor to oversee economic decision making in their local area.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-09-05T13:14:49.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540957/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540957/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","Regional Planning and Development: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to further develop the Northern Powerhouse agenda.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","43493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540958","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Soft Drinks Industry Levy consultation was launched on 18<sup>th</sup> August 2016. At the Budget in March, the Government announced that it would consult on the Levy during the summer and legislate in Finance Bill 2017, for implementation from April 2018. This timetable remains in place.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-09-08T11:27:27.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540958/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540958/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540958/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the Government's plans are for the implementation of the soft drinks industry levy; and if he will publish a timetable for the implementation of that levy.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","43494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540959","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-05","<p>No direct employees of HM Treasury, Office of Budget Responsibility, Government Internal Audit Agency and Debt Management Office are paid less than the rate defined by the Living Wage Foundation as a living wage. No direct employees are employed on zero hours contracts.</p><p> </p><p>The Government supports businesses that choose to pay the Living Wage however our prime policy is the National Minimum Wage for the low paid. This is independently set by the Low Pay Commission at a level that maximises their wages without reducing employment prospect. It is for workers and employers to decide the level of wages above the minimum wage based on current circumstances. This includes the Government as a procurer and an employer. Over 95%, around 20 million employees earn above the minimum wage and the majority of public sector workers currently earn above the Living Wage. Government will always award contracts on the basis of the best value for money for the taxpayers – which includes the low paid.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury does not hold information on wages paid by our suppliers.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-09-05T13:07:29.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540959/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540959/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","Treasury: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people working for his Department or its executive agencies on a (a) directly employed, (b) agency or (c) outsourced basis are paid less than the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation; and how many of those people are employed on zero-hours contracts.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","43512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540960","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-09","<p>Tackling money laundering and terrorist financing is a priority for the Government. The UK is a leading member of the international standard setter for anti-money laundering and counter terrorist financing, the Financial Action Task Force, and supports full compliance with the standards which we implement domestically. The UK will continue to cooperate closely with our international partners to improve the effectiveness of the standards, and to ensure the global anti-money regime is robust and responsive to emerging threats.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-09-09T10:40:56.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540960/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540960/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether it is his policy that existing money laundering regulations made under section 2(2) of the European Communities Act 1972 should remain in force in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540961","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-05","<p>New rules apply in the new State Pension scheme introduced from 6 April 2016. Individuals who reach State Pension age on or after that date are paid their new State Pension from the date they reach their State Pension age. Payments are made in arrears on a payday based on the individual’s National Insurance number. This means that in most cases the first payment may be in respect of a part of a week – that is from the day the individual reaches State Pension age to their first normal payday. The new State Pension is payable until the date of their death and a part week payment may also apply at the end of their claim.</p><p> </p><p>Under the State Pension system that applies to people who reached State Pension age before 6 April 2016, for those who did not move from a working age benefit to State Pension, the State Pension is payable only in full benefit weeks. This means that depending on the individual’s payday, as determined by their National Insurance number, their payment may not have begun from the day they reached their State Pension age. These arrangements for full week payment apply to both the start and the end of their claim for their State Pension and a full week is paid in respect of the week in which their death occurs.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-09-05T11:30:42.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540961/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540961/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 19 July 2016 to Question 42832, if he will allow part payments to cover the one to six day period between people reaching State Pension Age and their allocated pension payday.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","43605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540962","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-05","<p>My officials continue to work with the Department for Transport on the financial and contractual implications of any further extension of user discounts. A decision will be made on this in due course.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-09-05T13:04:22.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540962/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540962/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540962/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","River Mersey: Bridges","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether funding will be made available to Knowsley Council to enable residents who live in close proximity to the Mersey Gateway Bridge and Silver Jubilee Bridge to travel toll-free when those bridges open.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","43726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540963","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-08","<p>I am unable to comment on the tax affairs of individual companies.</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs applies the VAT rules for private companies consistently and fairly to ensure a level playing field. As reported in the National Audit Office's report, the UnitingCare Partnership is a limited liability partnership.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-09-08T11:39:21.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540963/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540963/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540963/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","UnitingCare Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 3.14 of the National Audit Office's investigation into the collapse of the UnitingCare Partnership contract, for what reasons HMRC did not approve UnitingCare's request to remove VAT liability.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","43601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540964","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-08","<p>Money laundering is a global problem that can undermine the integrity and stability of our financial markets and institutions. The UK was a founding member of the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) which sets the global standards to combat money laundering and terrorist financing, and the EU Commission and a majority of EU Member States are also FATF members. The UK will continue to play a leading role in tackling illicit financial flows through working with the FATF to ensure that standards are implemented effectively and through engaging bilaterally with countries on operational issues.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-09-08T10:44:47.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540964/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540964/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540964/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government plans to take to ensure continued cooperation with EU member states to prevent money laundering after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540965","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-09","<p>The creative industries make a valuable cultural contribution to the UK, they are also an important part of a dynamic and diversified economy.</p><p> </p><p>In its first two years the video games tax relief aided the production of 135 games, supporting £417 million of production spending in this country.</p><p> </p><p>The latest statistics on all of the creative sector tax reliefs can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/creative-industries-statistics-july-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/creative-industries-statistics-july-2016</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-09-09T10:42:53.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540965/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540965/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540965/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","Video Games: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the benefits to the UK economy of video games tax relief.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","43669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540966","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-05","<p>My officials continue to work with the Department for Transport on the financial and contractual implications of any further extension of user discounts. A decision will be made on this in due course.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-09-05T13:13:37.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540966/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540966/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540966/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","River Mersey: Bridges","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will extend the local discount scheme to residents across Merseyside to allow them to travel toll-free across the Mersey Gateway and Silver Jubilee bridges when they open in 2017.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","43666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540967","Church Commissioners","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Cathedral and Church Buildings Division of the Church of England is engaging with the ‘English Churches and Cathedrals Sustainability Review’ centrally on behalf of all the Anglican Cathedrals and Parish Churches in England. Engagement is currently at an early stage. Four workshops are being held in churches this month (September) to help inform a document that will then be widely consulted upon.</p><p> </p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman",,"2016-09-05T10:56:03.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540967/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540967/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540967/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2016-07-20","Churches: Blackburn","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, which churches and personnel in Preston and the rest of the Diocese of Blackburn have participated in the English Churches and Cathedrals Sustainability Review.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","43489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540968","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-05","<p>This independent report is for consideration by the Tees Valley Combined Authority and wider stakeholders. Government will not issue a formal response, but is committed to supporting Tees Valley Combined Authority relationship with Government across the wide range of areas identified in the report. Local leaders are planning a formal update event for the report in the Autumn.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2016-09-05T10:49:08.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540968/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540968/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/540968/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-20","Economic Growth: Tees Valley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will publish a response to the recommendations in the report by Lord Heseltine, entitled Tees Valley: opportunity unlimited, published in June 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","43525"
