"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541029","Department of Health","false","2016-09-05","<p>The legislation on food labelling sets out the content, format and expression of nutrition information on food labels. It is implemented in England by the Food Information Regulations 2014. Nutrition labelling for most pre-packed food and drink will be mandatory from 13 December 2016.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-09-05T11:55:41.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541029/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541029/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541029/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Food: Labelling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to standardise nutritional information in food and drink labelling.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","43583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541030","Department of Health","false","2016-09-05","<p>NHS England’s Commissioning through Evaluation (CtE) programme enables a limited number of patients to access treatments, such as patent foramen ovale closure and left atrial appendage occlusion, which are not routinely funded by the National Health Service. These are usually treatments which show significant promise for the future and enable a small number of patients to access them while new clinical and patient experience data are collected within a formal evaluation programme. This approach ensures that each CtE scheme provides valuable new data, beyond that already available from clinical trials, or where there is no clinical trial data, to inform future commissioning policy decisions.</p><p>During the analysis phase, NHS England’s published policy position for the treatment concerned will continue to apply. For patent foramen ovale closure and left atrial appendage occlusion this will mean that these procedures will not be routinely available within the NHS. However, patients already being treated as part of a CtE scheme will continue to receive appropriate follow-up care.</p><p>Once the CtE evaluation report is available, or if other significant clinical trial information becomes available more quickly, NHS England’s published policy for the treatment concerned will be reviewed and a decision will be made about whether NHS England will or will not make the treatment available within the NHS.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-09-05T08:58:52.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541030/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541030/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541030/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Strokes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the treatment of strokes of withdrawing access to patent foramen ovale closure and left atrial appendage occlusion during the commissioning through evaluation analysis phase.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","43555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541031","Department of Health","false","2016-09-05","<p>No such discussions have taken place.</p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) published a clinical guideline on Urinary tract infection in under 16s: diagnosis and management (CG54) in August 2007. NICE has also published Quality Standards on Urinary tract infection in children and young people (QS36) in July 2013 and Urinary tract infections in adults (QS90) in June 2015.</p><p> </p><p>NICE periodically reviews its technology appraisal methods and processes to ensure that they remain appropriate in the light of wider developments.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-09-05T11:23:02.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541031/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541031/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541031/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Urinary Tract Infections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with NICE about the effectiveness of guidelines to tackle urinary tract infections that are (a) acute and (b) chronic.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","43528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541032","Department of Health","false","2016-09-05","<p>No civil servants employed by the Department or its executive agencies: Public Health England and the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency are paid less than the Living Wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.</p><p> </p><p>The Department currently has no agency worker paid less than the living wage. As at 22 July 2016, 23 people employed via outsourced contract companies were paid less than the Living Wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation, none of these were on zero hours contracts. Six other people, on zero rated hours are paid the Living Wage or more.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s executive agencies do not routinely collect information on the salaries of employees working for their contracted companies. However, all service providers are required to comply with the law in respect of the ‘National Living Wage’ or the ‘minimum wage’ where appropriate.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-09-05T08:33:30.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541032/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541032/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541032/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Department of Health: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people working for his Department or its executive agencies on a (a) directly employed, (b) agency or (c) outsourced basis are paid less than the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation; and how many of those people are employed on zero-hours contracts.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","43517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541033","Department of Health","false","2016-09-05","<p>We launched <em>Childhood Obesity: A Plan for Action</em> on 18 August. A copy of the plan is attached and is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/546588/Childhood_obesity_2016__2__acc.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/546588/Childhood_obesity_2016__2__acc.pdf</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-09-05T12:06:08.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541033/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541033/answer","PQ43527 Childhood Obesity Strategy.pdf","PQ43527 Childhood Obesity Strategy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541033/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Obesity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to tackle obesity in (a) the North East and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","43527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541034","Department of Health","false","2016-09-05","<p>Data for 2016 is not yet available.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-09-05T11:50:25.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541034/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541034/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Abortion: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many abortions (a) overall and (b) where Downs syndrome had been identified were carried out at each (i) NHS hospital, (ii) clinic and (iii) surgery in Lancashire in 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","43487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541035","Department of Health","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Department’s National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) invested £4.1 million in ear disease research in 2014-15 (the latest year for which data is currently available).</p><p> </p><p>The NIHR is investing £6.2 million over five years (2012-17) in the Biomedical Research Unit in Deafness and Hearing Problems at Nottingham University Hospitals NHS Trust and the University of Nottingham.</p><p> </p><p>The NIHR has launched a new, open competition for biomedical research centre funding from April 2017 to March 2022. In this competition, a number of clinical areas of particular strategic importance to the health of patients are highlighted including deafness and hearing problems.</p><p> </p><p>Current NIHR-funded awards relating to hearing loss include a £1.6 million research professorship to develop the evidence base for Ear, Nose and Throat medicine and surgery, and a £1.3 million feasibility study of an implantable middle-ear microphone.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-09-05T12:03:55.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541035/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541035/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Hearing Impairment: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what research into hearing loss at what cost his Department has commissioned in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","43604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541036","Department of Health","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Department awarded the National Childbirth Trust (NCT) an Innovation Excellence and Strategic Development Grant in 2015-16 under the Innovation strand.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The grant is funding a Perinatal Mental health project. The main aims of the NCT project are, to promote positive maternal mental health and support engagement with specialist services for women experiencing perinatal mental illness.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-09-05T08:35:06.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541036/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541036/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","National Childbirth Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what grants for what purpose his Department is making to the National Childbirth Trust in 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","43613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541037","Department of Health","false","2016-09-05","<p>The policy responsibility for welfare reform sits with the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP). The Department of Health has not made a separate assessment of the effect of welfare reform on health inequalities in England.</p><p> </p><p>Although no assessment has been made in England, DWP has engaged across government on its proposals for welfare reform. The Department of Health has been involved in discussions on the introduction of Universal Credit and its impact on health inequalities for programmes such as Healthy Start and Help with Health Costs.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-09-05T12:34:30.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541037/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541037/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Health: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of welfare reform on health inequalities in (a) St Helens North constituency, (b) Merseyside and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","43623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541039","Department of Health","false","2016-09-05","<p>NHS Property Services is a limited company 100% owned by the Secretary of State for Health, to whom it is accountable. Within the Department, Ministerial responsibility for NHS Property Services is delegated to my noble Friend the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State (Lord Prior).</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-09-05T09:41:29.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541039/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541039/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Department of Health: NHS Property Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which Minister in his Department is responsible for NHS Property Services.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","43611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541040","Department of Health","false","2016-09-08","<p>This is an employer and employee matter between the East Lancashire Hospitals NHS Trust and Mr Aditya Agrawal respectively. The Department cannot comment on individual employment matters that are the responsibility of independent organisations, and that are subject to ongoing legal proceedings or on matters relating to individual clinical cases or other personal information. We understand that the cost to East Lancashire Trust of legal proceedings concerning Mr Agrawal is £296,848.42 to date, and that the Trust does not have insurance costs for legal awards in the event of the Trust or one of its employees being subject to legal action for defamation.</p><p> </p>","South West Surrey","Mr Jeremy Hunt","43638 ; 43639 ; 43640 ; 43641 ; 43643 ; 43730 ; 43925 ; 43926 ; 43927 ; 43928","2016-09-08T15:06:23.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541040/answer","Biography information for Mr Jeremy Hunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541040/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Aditya Agrawal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the reasons given for the dismissal of Mr Agrawal were related to clinical concerns.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","43642"
